MARCUS ANNAEUS LUCANUS.

LUcAN was born at Corduba, in southern Spain, 39 Am. His father was a brother of the philosopher Seneca. His · father moved to Rome when he was a baby, and there he received his training, which was the best that the metropolis afforded. Cornutus the Stoic was one of his teachers. His talents early developed, and even as a boy he began to declaim his own verses with great applause. When Nero ascended the throne, he was friendly to Lucan, but as the emperor was also a composer of verses there was rivalry between them. When the two entered the same public contest and the prize was awarded to the commoner‚ Nero forbade him to publish or recite any more of his compositions. Lucan, angered by this act of tyranny, entered into the conspiracy of Piso. The plot was discovered. Lucan, by a promise of par-don, was induced to turn state's evidence. He denounced his own
